
🟨 Chain of events in a Vite + Fastify setup:
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
- vite --> pronounced 'veet'

- Combination of Vite and Fastify --> to build full-stack applications
	- 1) Vite --> frontend build tool
	- 2) Fastify --> a low-overhead Node.js framework --> backend.

- 1) Vite consists of two main parts:
	1) development server --> leverages native ES modules in the browser
	2) build command --> bundles your code with Rollup for highly optimized static assets 
				in production

- 2) Fastify offers features like 
	- schema-based validation and a 
	- powerful plugin architecture
	
- Development: npm start and the Dev Mode
	- npm start command is configured to launch the application in development mode
	- npm start --> running a script that starts your Fastify server
	- Fastify server is configured to use Vite as a middleware
		- using a plugin like @fastify/vite
		- allows Fastify to hand off certain requests to Vite's development server.
	
- Two servers running
	- 1) Fastify Server (e.g., on port 3000):
		- main application server. 
		- It handles API routes, server-side logic, and, 
		- through the Vite middleware, serves your frontend application.
	
	- 2) Vite Dev Server (e.g., on its default port 5173):
		- server is responsible for serving your frontend assets 
		- (like JavaScript, CSS, and images) during development.
		- It's the engine behind the rapid development experience.
		
🟣 User navigates to http://localhost:3000
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

- The initial request hits the Fastify server.

- The @fastify/vite middleware intercepts this request.

- For the initial HTML page, the middleware will likely use Vite to process index.html file. 

- Vite injects its client-side code for Hot Module Replacement (HMR) and 

- then sends the processed HTML back to the browser.


🟣 Vite in Action
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

- The browser receives the index.html file and starts parsing it. 
- It will find <script type="module"> tags that point to index.js, i.e. entry point.
- The browser then sends requests for these JavaScript modules source code.

- These requests are intercepted by the Vite dev server. 
- Vite serves these files directly from your source code, 
	leveraging the browser's native ES module support. 
- This avoids bundling the entire application during development.

- As you make changes to your frontend code, the Vite dev server uses HMR to push 
	only the updated modules to the browser, 
	resulting in near-instantaneous updates without a full page reload


🟣 Fetch data from the backend
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

- When frontend application needs to fetch data from the backend, 
	it will make API requests (e.g., to /api/users).

- These API requests are also sent to the Fastify server on port 3000.

- Since these requests don't correspond to frontend assets that Vite needs to handle, 
	they are processed by your Fastify application's routes.

- Fastify handlers will execute, interact with a database or other services, and 
	return a JSON response to the browser.
	
- Vite's dev server can be configured to proxy API requests to the Fastify backend.
- This makes it seem as though the frontend and backend are running on the same origin 
	from the browser's perspective.


🟣 In development mode:: Fastify VS Vite
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

1. browser requests http://localhost:3000.

2. The Fastify server receives the request.

3. The @fastify/vite middleware uses Vite to process and 
   serve your project's root index.html.
   
4. Vite injects its client-side code for Hot Module Replacement (HMR) into this HTML file 
   before sending it to the browser.

5. The browser receives the processed index.html and then requests the JavaScript module 
   index.js specified in the script tag.

6. This request for a .js file is handled by the Vite dev server, which serves it directly.


🟣 index.html VS index.js
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------	

- For your JavaScript application, index.js is indeed the entry point.
- This is where your application's logic begins, 
	where you might import other components, and 
	where you tell your framework (like React or Vue) where to attach itself in the DOM.

- For the browser, the ultimate entry point is always an index.html file. 
- Vite treats it as the entry point to your entire application
- A browser's job is to render an HTML document. 
- When you type a URL, the browser requests and receives an HTML file. 
- HTML file tells the browser what other resources to load, such as CSS, images, JavaScript files.


🟢 Production Mode: Creating the Production Artifacts
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

- npm run build > executes Vite's build command.
- Vite takes application's source code and: 

- Bundles: JavaScript and CSS into a few highly optimized files using Rollup.

- Minifies: It minifies the code to reduce its size.

- Code Splitting: splits the code into smaller chunks, so the browser only needs to 
  download the code necessary for the initial page load.
  
- Static Assets: It processes and optimizes your static assets like images.

- The output of this process is a dist directory containing all the static assets 
  for your frontend application.
  

🟢 The Production Server: Fastify in action
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

- In production, the Vite dev server is no longer needed. 
- The Fastify server takes on the full responsibility of serving both 
  the frontend and the backend.
  
- The npm start command in a production environment will now simply start the Fastify server.

- The configuration will be different from the development setup:

- The @fastify/vite plugin, when not in development mode, will automatically look 
  for the production build in the dist directory.
  
- Fastify will be configured to serve the static files from this dist directory. 
  This is typically done using a plugin like @fastify/static.
  

🟢 When a user accesses' application in a production environment:
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 

- The request hits the Fastify server.
- For the initial page load, Fastify serves the index.html file from the dist directory.
- The browser receives the HTML and finds <script> and <link> tags pointing to 
  the optimized, bundled JavaScript and CSS files.
- The browser then requests these static assets from the Fastify server.
- Fastify serves these bundled files from the dist directory.
- Any subsequent API requests from the frontend are also handled by the same Fastify server.
- browser receives a highly optimized version of your application, leading to 
  faster load times and a better user experience.



